article.description: Gary Payton had 25 points and 12 assists and Rashard Lewis scored 17 points as the SuperSonics routed the Nuggets, 104-77, avenging a loss 24 hours ago.
article.headline: Rebound turnaround: Seattle outboards Denver 52-32
article.linkText: Sonics turn the tables on Nuggets in back-to-back finale
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics didn't need to be reminded how poorly they played in the third quarter in Denver.
Payton

Gary Payton had 25 points and 12 assists and the Seattle SuperSonics, beaten in Denver the previous night, handed the Nuggets their 13th consecutive road loss, 104-77 on Saturday night. "They just had a good third quarter," Payton said. "Tonight, we played 48 minutes instead of 24 and it was a lot easier." In Seattle's 96-90 loss in Denver on Friday night, the Sonics were outscored 36-15 after leading by 13 points at halftime. On Saturday night, Seattle outscored the Nuggets 32-12 in the third. "We gave one away last night because they outworked us," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "We all feel sick about that loss last night. We know that we gave it away." Nick Van Exel scored 24 of his 28 points in the first half for the Nuggets, whose road record fell to 2-15. Denver hasn't won on the road since Nov. 17, in Seattle. Rashard Lewis scored 17 points for Seattle. Vin Baker added 15 points, and Art Long had 12 points and 11 rebounds. "We had a lead going into halftime tonight, like Friday night, and we just vowed that we weren't going to do the same things we did in the second half in Denver," Baker said. Voshon Lenard scored 16 points for Denver, while teammate Zendon Hamilton had 12 rebounds and 10 points. The Sonics, outrebounded 55-33 Friday, outrebounded the Nuggets 52-32. The Sonics came into the game averaging 39.9 rebounds a game, the second worst in the NBA to Detroit's 38.3. "We talked about having pride in rebounding," McMillan said. "It's weird, it's real weird," Van Exel said. "We play one way at home one night and the opposite way on the road the next night. It doesn't make any sense." Van Exel said he didn't get physically tired in the second half after shooting 9-for-14 in the first half. He attempted only five shots in the first half. "They just did a good job on me defensively," Van Exel said. "They played a complete game tonight and we didn't. It's tough to win on the road when you can't maintain your intensity for four quarters." But the Sonics said Payton, who guarded Van Exel, outconditioned him. "Gary really worked," McMillan said. "Van Exel looked a little winded. Everything he made was a tough shot and that's about all you can do with him." Denver coach Mike Evans wasn't surprised at the 24-hour turnaround. The Nuggets are playing without their best inside player, Antonio McDyess, who underwent surgery in October to repair the patella tendon in his left knee. "We're just short," Evans said. "Some nights we're going to be good and some nights are going to be tough. When teams are able to dominate us inside, it's going to be tough. We have to do a better job on the road." Denver lost for the 13th time in 15 games. The Sonics beat the Nuggets for the first time in three games this season. Seattle put the Nuggets away with a 17-3 run to end the third quarter, pushing a 67-54 lead to an 84-57 advantage. In the final minute, Brent Barry and Desmond Mason each had a dunk, and Payton scored on a fastbreak layup. After Baker missed a free throw, Mason grabbed an offensive rebound and scored on a tip-in with 2 minutes left in the third period to give Seattle a 78-56 lead. The Sonics led 52-45 at halftime. Mason delighting the Key Arena crowd with an alley-oop dunk early in the second quarter that gave Seattle a 36-27 lead.

Game notes
The first 10,000 fans who showed up for the game received a Gary Payton bobblehead doll. The bobblehead giveaway was the first of four the Sonics have planned this season. The team also will give away Rashard Lewis, Desmond Mason and Nate McMillan bobbleheads. ... The Sonics have a 13-6 record at home.
